# Brute force and arriving at hashMap
1. Brute force: we can go through each row and column of the grid and see if they have the same elements in the same order. If they do, we increase the count. 
The problem with this approach is we will be checking twice for column with same values: eg 2, 5, 2, 2 occurs 2 times and we will be rechecking this. This can be avoided using a hashMap to store the row.

Store each row as key in the hashMap i.e array 1,2,2,1 will be key and the value will be the count of 1,2,2,1 in rows

Iterate through the columns and increment the count by value if its Present in the hashMap.


# Appoach.
1. Create hashMap <String, Integer> hashMap.
why String?? As array hash is based on reference we convert it to string and store.
2. For each row in grid. convert row to String and store in hashMap. increase count if already existing.
3. For every column convert the col to String and check if present in hashMap, incerase the ans by value in hashMap.
4. return count

