solutions.content:
My first intuition was that it would be rather easy to hash each row, count the frequency of each hash and then do the for each column, adding the frequency previously found to the result for each match.

In order to do so, a normal `string` would not cut it, since `char`s go with `7` bits and cut out the rest, so we will get tons of collisions from that. But with `16` bits, we can cover almost completely the full range (to go up to `10e5` we would have needed `17`, but with `16` we do well enough to avoid any collisions with all the test cases, although you might argue that a few such cases might be created to let us slip with this approach).

We will start `using` `u16String` as our `hashType`, then declaring our usual support variables:
* `hashFreq` will map hashes to their respective frequence;
* `res` is our usual accumulator variable, initially set to `0`;
* `len` will store the size of the provided `grid`;
* `tmp` is our helper string, preset to be `len` characters.

We will start parsing the rows first and for each `row` in `grid`, we will:
* declare our writer pointer `w` with initial value of `0`;
* loop through each value `c` in `row` and:
    * write it in `tmp[w]`;
    * advance `w` by `1`, ready to write in the next cell;
* increase `hashFreq[tmp]` by `1`.

With our hashes so computed for each row, time to do the same for each column `x` in grid and we will:
* loop through each row `y` in `grid` and write `grid[y][c]` in `tmp[y]`;
* assign the result of `hashFreq.find(tmp)` to `it`;
* if we ever found such a value (ie: `it != end(hashFreq)`), we will then increase `res` by that value (ie: `it->second`).

Once done, we can finally `return` `res` :)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n^2)$$

# Code
```cpp
using hashType = u16string;

class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>> &grid) {
        // support variables
        unordered_map<hashType, int> hashFreq;
        int res = 0, len = grid.size();
        hashType tmp(len, '*');
        // parsing rows
        for (auto &row: grid) {
            // creating the row hash
            int w = 0;
            for (int c: row) tmp[w++] = c;
            // storing the hash
            hashFreq[tmp]++;
        }
        // parsing columns
        for (int x = 0; x < len; x++) {
            // creating the column hash
            for (int y = 0; y < len; y++) tmp[y] = grid[y][x];
            // checking if we found the same hash before
            auto it = hashFreq.find(tmp);
            if (it != end(hashFreq)) res += it->second;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
# Brag
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/30054297-a35b-49b2-8dc1-25591b39578a_1686687724.9152997.png)


Next I tried my other idea, a `Trie` approach, since this again goes well when you need to check your matches in a given dictionary and in a way I was doing that with my string hashing, but could have been done MAYBE better with something like this DS.

In this approach we will create a `Trie` `struct` which will just have two properties:
* `matches`, initially set to `0`, will store all the matches we have for a given chain (it will be increased only for the end-of-chain nodes);
* `children` is a set of `bucketSize` pointers we will use to connect each node to its descendents on a chain.

In our main function we will proceed similarly to the previous approach, declaring a first `Trie` node `root` and a `Trie` pointer `curr` instead of `tmp`.

For the rows we will then proceed for each character `row` and:
* `reset` `curr` to be `root`;
* for each value `c`, we will:
    * try to get its modulo `bucketSize` by consistently subtracting it `while` `c >= bucketSize` (see the third solution here for my thoughts on actually using `%`);
    * check if we do not have `curr->children[c]` and if so, we will create it as a new `Trie` node;
    * advance `curr` to be `curr->children[c]`;
* finally, having reached the last node of this chain, we will increase `curr->matches` by `1`.

Again, we will proceed specularly for each column, getting `grid[y][x]` as `c` and with two sole differences:
* whenever we do not find a node to advance next (ie: `curr->children[c] == NULL`) we will `break`;
* at the end of each inner loop, we will increase `res` by `curr->matches` (which is going to be `0` every time we hit `break` before reaching the end of a previously created chain).

Tweaking `bucketSize` has a MASSIVE effect on performance and turns out using a small enough number (initially I tried `1337`, but quickly run out of memory; it was slow but working with `137` and rather fast for other significantly smaller values, while still burning way more memory than the string hashing approach):

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
- 
```cpp
constexpr int bucketSize = 27;

struct Trie {
    int matches = 0;
    Trie *children[bucketSize] = {};
};

class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>> &grid) {
        // support variables
        Trie *root = new Trie(), *curr;
        int res = 0, len = grid.size();
        // parsing rows
        for (auto &row: grid) {
            // creating Trie path for the row
            curr = root;
            for (int c: row) {
                while (c >= bucketSize) c -= bucketSize;
                if (!curr->children[c]) curr->children[c] = new Trie();
                curr = curr->children[c];
            }
            // adding the frequence
            curr->matches++;
        }
        // parsing columns
        for (int x = 0; x < len; x++) {
            // checking Trie path for the column
            curr = root;
            for (int y = 0, c; y < len; y++) {
                c = grid[y][x];
                while (c >= bucketSize) c -= bucketSize;
                if (!curr->children[c]) break;
                curr = curr->children[c];
            }
            // adding the frequence, if any
            res += curr->matches;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

As a proof of how expensive is to compute a modulo, this alternative version while I don't just use repeated subtraction to reduce all the numbers above `bucketSize` ran actually a bit slower after several tests (I am sure it would be the opposite with `grid` being populated with larger numbers, but that is really telling):

```cpp
constexpr int bucketSize = 19;

struct Trie {
    int matches = 0;
    Trie *children[bucketSize] = {};
};

class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>> &grid) {
        // support variables
        Trie *root = new Trie(), *curr;
        int res = 0, len = grid.size();
        // parsing rows
        for (auto &row: grid) {
            // creating Trie path for the row
            curr = root;
            for (int c: row) {
                c %= bucketSize;
                if (!curr->children[c]) curr->children[c] = new Trie();
                curr = curr->children[c];
            }
            // adding the frequence
            curr->matches++;
        }
        // parsing columns
        for (int x = 0; x < len; x++) {
            // checking Trie path for the column
            curr = root;
            for (int y = 0, c; y < len; y++) {
                c = grid[y][x];
                c %= bucketSize;
                if (!curr->children[c]) break;
                curr = curr->children[c];
            }
            // adding the frequence, if any
            res += curr->matches;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Needless to say, I wanted to try also with a hashmap for `children`; boring, and way slower and more inefficient than expected:

```cpp
struct Trie {
    int matches = 0;
    unordered_map<int, Trie*> children;
};

class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>> &grid) {
        // support variables
        Trie *root = new Trie(), *curr;
        int res = 0, len = grid.size();
        // parsing rows
        for (auto &row: grid) {
            // creating Trie path for the row
            curr = root;
            for (int c: row) {
