# Intuition
i thought we can simply go through each row and store the numbers as a string in a HashMap with their frequency. And then we can traverse through each column and store the number of column in a string to compare it with the HashMap elements after each column iteration ends.

# Approach
1- I created a HashMap to Store each row elements as a String with their frequencies. 
2- I started with row wise traversal where i used a StringBuilder to easily concatenate the values as a String.
**The reason i used '#' to append after each value is due to the case where in a row there might be all same digit numbers such as in example [[11,1],[1,11]] where when you will store the number as String without appending '#' you will get 111 and 111 which is completely wrong.**
3- Then i am just updating the frequencies.
4- Now i started with column wise traversal and storing every column as a string and then looking if the column string is present in the hashmap.
5- if it is present in the hashmap ,then add their frequencies to the count

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
from my analysis it is -

1. O(N^2) for row traversal 
2. O(N^2) for column traversal 
3. O(N) for hashMap lookup and Insertions 
