# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We create another vector of vector named v such that the columns of original grid are the rows of 'v'.
After that we compare the rows of the original grid to each row of the new grid and increment the count if both the rows are totally same.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N*N)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N*N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n=grid.size();
        vector<vector<int>> v=grid;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                v[i][j]=grid[j][i];
            }
        }
        int cnt=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                if(grid[i]==v[j])cnt++;
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};
